1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,220
Just below base exception is the exception class,

2

00:00:03,220  -->  00:00:07,020
which is like a senior manager overseeing most errors we encounter.

3

00:00:07,020  -->  00:00:09,480
When we refer to handling exceptions,

4

00:00:09,480  -->  00:00:12,920
we usually mean those derived from exception.

5

00:00:12,920  -->  00:00:18,240
It covers a wide range of errors from value error to type error,

6

00:00:18,240  -->  00:00:22,940
and is a great catch all for general issues that don't need special handling.

7

00:00:22,940  -->  00:00:24,620
Similar to base exception,

8

00:00:24,620  -->  00:00:30,220
we can write our except statement and switch base exception to just exception.

9

00:00:30,220  -->  00:00:33,740
Using exception as the default catch in our code is often

10

00:00:33,740  -->  00:00:37,940
recommended because it won't interfere with our system exiting exceptions,

11

00:00:37,940  -->  00:00:40,640
like system exit or keyboard interrupt,

12

00:00:40,640  -->  00:00:44,260
which we will learn about in a little bit.
